  DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN

    The ddaattee(1) utility displays the current date and time when invoked
    without arguments. Providing arguments will format the date and time in a
    user-defined way.

    If the argument provided is the month (mm, as a number), day (dd), hour
    (HH, as a number using the 24-hour system), minute (MM) and optionally the
    year (yy--current year if omitted), the utility attempts to set the system
    date and time. Only a user with appropriate privileges may set the date.

  OOPPTTIIOONNSS

    --bb
        Accept the date in BSD-style "ccyymmddHHMM.SS". The default is
        "mmddHHMMyy" to conform to the standard.
        Only the minutes (MM) are required; hours (HH), days (dd), month (mm),
        the century (CC), and seconds (SS) are all optional.

    --jj
        Do not apply the change. This is useful for testing.

    --nn
	The -n option suppresses the behavior of informing the time daemon
        so that all machines in the local group have the time updated.
        This is the Interix default behavior and causes the time to be set
        only on the current machine.

    --rr seconds
        Display the date and time in seconds from the UNIX Epoch (January 1,
        1970)

    --uu
        Display the date in Universal Coordinated Time (UCT).

    ++format
